# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gate-driver
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] A **bootstrap** circuit is one where part of the output of an amplifier stage is applied to the input, so as to alter the input impedance of the amplifier.
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] When applied deliberately, the intention is usually to increase rather than decrease the impedance.
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] In the domain of MOSFET circuits, bootstrapping is commonly used to mean pulling up the operating point of a transistor above the power supply rail.
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] The same term has been used somewhat more generally for dynamically altering the operating point of an operational amplifier (by shifting both its positive and negative supply rail) in order to increase its output voltage swing (relative to the ground).
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] In the sense used in this paragraph, bootstrapping an operational amplifier means "using a signal to drive the reference point of the op-amp's power supplies".
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] A more sophisticated use of this rail bootstrapping technique is to alter the non-linear C/V characteristic of the inputs of a JFET op-amp in order to decrease its distortion.
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] In analog circuit designs, a bootstrap circuit is an arrangement of components deliberately intended to alter the input impedance of a circuit.
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] Usually it is intended to increase the impedance, by using a small amount of positive feedback, usually over two stages.
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] This was often necessary in the early days of bipolar transistors, which inherently have quite a low input impedance.
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] Because the feedback is positive, such circuits can suffer from poor stability and noise performance compared to ones that don't bootstrap.
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] An N-MOSFET/IGBT needs a significantly positive charge (*VGS > V*th) applied to the gate in order to turn on.
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] Using only N-channel MOSFET/IGBT devices is a common cost reduction method due largely to die size reduction (there are other benefits as well).
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] However, using nMOS devices in place of pMOS devices means that a voltage higher than the power rail supply (V+) is needed in order to bias the transistor into linear operation (minimal current limiting) and thus avoid significant heat loss.
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] A bootstrap capacitor is connected from the supply rail (V+) to the output voltage.
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] Usually the source terminal of the N-MOSFET is connected to the cathode of a recirculation diode allowing for efficient management of stored energy in the typically inductive load (See Flyback diode).
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] Due to the charge storage characteristics of a capacitor, the bootstrap voltage will rise above (V+) providing the needed gate drive voltage.
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] A bootstrap circuit is often used in each half-bridge of an all-N-MOSFET H-bridge.
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] When the low-side N-FET is on, current from the power rail (V+) flows through the bootstrap diode and charges the bootstrap capacitor through that low-side N-FET.
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] A MOSFET/IGBT is a voltage-controlled device which, in theory, will not have any gate current.
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] This makes it possible to utilize the charge inside the capacitor for control purposes.
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] However, eventually the capacitor will lose its charge due to parasitic gate current and non-ideal (i.e. finite) internal resistance, so this scheme is only used where there is a steady pulse present.
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] This is because the pulsing action allows for the capacitor to discharge (at least partially if not completely).
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] Most control schemes that use a bootstrap capacitor force the high side driver (N-MOSFET) off for a minimum time to allow for the capacitor to refill.
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] This means that the duty cycle will always need to be less than 100% to accommodate for the parasitic discharge unless the leakage is accommodated for in another manner.
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] In switch-mode power supplies, the control circuits are powered from the output.
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] To start the power supply, a leakage resistance can be used to trickle-charge the supply rail for the control circuit to start it oscillating.
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] This approach is less costly and simpler than providing a separate linear power supply just to start the regulator circuit.
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] AC amplifiers can use bootstrapping to increase output swing.
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] A capacitor (usually referred as *bootstrap capacitor*) is connected from the output of the amplifier to the bias circuit, providing bias voltages that exceed the power supply voltage.
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] Emitter followers can provide rail-to-rail output in this way, which is a common technique in class AB audio amplifiers.
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] Within an integrated circuit a bootstrap method is used to allow internal address and clock distribution lines to have an increased voltage swing.
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] The bootstrap circuit uses a coupling capacitor, formed from the gate/source capacitance of a transistor, to drive a signal line to slightly greater than the supply voltage.
[src:gate-driver/bootstrapping-electronics] Some all-pMOS integrated circuits such as the Intel 4004 and the Intel 8008 use that 2-transistor "bootstrap load" circuit.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] A **gate driver** is a power amplifier that accepts a low-power input from a controller IC and produces a high-current drive input for the gate of a high-power transistor such as an IGBT or power MOSFET.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] Gate drivers can be provided either on-chip or as a discrete module.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] In essence, a gate driver consists of a level shifter in combination with an amplifier.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] A gate driver IC serves as the interface between control signals (digital or analog controllers) and power switches (IGBTs, MOSFETs, SiC MOSFETs, and GaN HEMTs).
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] An integrated gate-driver solution reduces design complexity, development time, bill of materials (BOM), and board space while improving reliability over discretely-implemented gate-drive solutions.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] Using this mixed-signal HVIC technology, both high-voltage level-shifting circuits and low-voltage analog and digital circuits can be implemented.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] The HVIC gate drivers with floating switches are well-suited for topologies requiring high-side, half-bridge, and three-phase configurations.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] In contrast to bipolar transistors, MOSFETs do not require continuous base current to remain in the on-state, as long as they are not being switched on or off.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] The isolated gate-electrode of the MOSFET forms a capacitor (gate capacitor), which must be charged or discharged each time the MOSFET is switched on or off.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] where $f_{s}$ is the switching frequency.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] Similarly, to switch the transistor off, this charge must be dissipated, i.e. the gate capacitor must be discharged.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] When a transistor is switched on or off, it does not immediately switch from a non-conducting to a conducting state; and may transiently support both a high voltage and conduct a high current.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] Consequently, when gate current is applied to a transistor to cause it to switch, a certain amount of heat is generated which can, in some cases, be enough to destroy the transistor.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] Therefore, it is necessary to keep the switching time as short as possible, so as to minimize switching loss.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] Typical switching times are in the range of microseconds.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] The switching time of a transistor is inversely proportional to the amount of current used to charge the gate.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] Therefore, switching currents are often required in the range of several hundred milliamperes, or even in the range of amperes.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] For typical gate voltages of approximately 10-15V, several watts of power may be required to drive the switch.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] When large currents are switched at high frequencies, e.g. in DC-to-DC converters or large electric motors, multiple transistors are sometimes provided in parallel, so as to provide sufficiently high switching currents and switching power.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] The switching signal for a transistor is usually generated by a logic circuit or a microcontroller, which provides an output signal that typically is limited to a few milliamperes of current.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] Consequently, a transistor which is directly driven by such a signal would switch very slowly, with correspondingly high power loss.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] During switching, the gate capacitor of the transistor may draw current so quickly that it causes a current overdraw in the logic circuit or microcontroller, causing overheating which leads to permanent damage or even complete destruction of the chip.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] To prevent this from happening, a gate driver is provided between the microcontroller output signal and the power transistor.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] Charge pumps are often used in H-bridges in *high side drivers* for gate driving the high side n-channel power MOSFETs and IGBTs.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] These devices are used because of their good performance, but require a gate drive voltage a few volts above the power rail.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] When the centre of a half bridge goes low the capacitor is charged via a diode, and this charge is used to later drive the gate of the high side FET gate a few volts above the source or emitter pin's voltage so as to switch it on.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] This strategy works well provided the bridge is regularly switched and avoids the complexity of having to run a separate power supply and permits the more efficient n-channel devices to be used for both high and low switches.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] During switching transitions, a power semiconductor device simultaneously sustains substantial voltage and current.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] where $t_{r}$ is the rise time, $t_{f}$ is the fall time, and $f_{s}$ is the switching frequency.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] To reduce switching losses, the transition intervals must be made as short as practical.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] Because switching time is inversely related to the available gate drive current, peak gate currents ranging from several hundred milliamperes to several amperes are commonly required in power electronic applications.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] Modern gate driver integrated circuits typically provide peak source and sink currents in the range of 1–10 A.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] At typical gate voltages of 10–15 V and high switching frequencies, such as those used in DC-to-DC converters and motor drives, the gate-drive circuitry may dissipate several watts of power, particularly when multiple devices are connected in parallel.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] Logic circuits and microcontrollers typically provide output currents of only a few milliamperes.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] Directly driving the gate of a power MOSFET or IGBT from such outputs would result in slow switching transitions and increased switching losses.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] In addition, the high transient current required to charge and discharge the gate capacitance may exceed the current capability of the control device.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] A gate driver provides current amplification and electrical buffering between the control circuitry and the power device.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] This allows rapid charging and discharging of the gate capacitance, reduces switching losses, and improves overall system reliability.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] In half-bridge and full-bridge converter topologies, N-channel MOSFETs or IGBTs are commonly used on both the low and high sides because of their lower conduction losses compared to P-channel devices.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] However, driving a high-side N-channel device requires a gate voltage several volts higher than its source potential.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] A widely used technique for high-side gate driving is the bootstrap method.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] When the low-side device conducts and the switching node is near ground potential, a bootstrap capacitor is charged through a diode from a low-voltage supply.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] When the high-side device is turned on, the stored charge raises the gate voltage above the source potential, enabling conduction.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] The bootstrap technique eliminates the need for a separate isolated power supply for the high-side driver and simplifies circuit implementation.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] However, it requires periodic switching to refresh the bootstrap capacitor and is generally unsuitable for continuous 100% duty-cycle operation without additional circuitry.
[src:gate-driver/gate-driver] Wide-bandgap semiconductor devices such as silicon carbide (SiC) MOSFETs and gallium nitride (GaN) HEMTs require specialized gate driver designs due to their high switching speeds, higher $dv/dt$ (which may exceed 100 V/ns), lower gate threshold voltages, and tighter gate voltage tolerances.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] Although the term *Miller effect* normally refers to capacitance, any impedance connected between the input and another node exhibiting gain can modify the amplifier input impedance via this effect.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] These properties of the Miller effect are generalized in the Miller theorem.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] The Miller capacitance due to undesired parasitic capacitance between the output and input of active devices like transistors and vacuum tubes is a major factor limiting their gain at high frequencies.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] When Miller published his work in 1919, he was working on vacuum tube triodes.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] The same analysis applies to modern devices such as bipolar junction and field-effect transistors.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] Consider a circuit of an ideal inverting voltage amplifier of gain $-A_{v}$ with an impedance Z connected between its input and output nodes.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] The output voltage is therefore $V_{o}=-A_{v}V_{i}$ .
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] This **Miller capacitance** $C_{M}$ is the physical capacitance C multiplied by the factor $(1+A_{v})$ .
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] As most amplifiers are inverting ( $A_{v}$ as defined above is positive), the effective capacitance at their inputs is increased due to the Miller effect.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] This can reduce the bandwidth of the amplifier, restricting its range of operation to lower frequencies.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] The tiny junction and stray capacitances between the base and collector terminals of a Darlington transistor, for example, may be drastically increased by the Miller effects due to its high gain, lowering the high frequency response of the device.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] It is also important to note that the Miller capacitance is the capacitance seen looking into the input.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] If looking for all of the RC time constants (poles) it is important to include as well the capacitance seen by the output.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] The capacitance on the output is often neglected since it sees ${C}({1+{\tfrac {1}{A_{v}}}})$ and amplifier outputs are typically low impedance.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] However if the amplifier has a high impedance output, such as if a gain stage is also the output stage, then this RC can have a significant impact on the performance of the amplifier.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] This is when pole splitting techniques are used.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] The Miller effect may also be exploited to synthesize larger capacitors from smaller ones.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] One such example is in the stabilization of feedback amplifiers, where the required capacitance may be too large to practically include in the circuit.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] This may be particularly important in the design of integrated circuits, where capacitors can consume significant area, increasing costs.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] The Miller effect may be undesired in many cases, and approaches may be sought to lower its impact.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] Several such techniques are used in the design of amplifiers.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] A current buffer stage may be added at the output to lower the gain $A_{v}$ between the input and output terminals of the amplifier (though not necessarily the overall gain).
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] For example, a common base may be used as a current buffer at the output of a common emitter stage, forming a cascode.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] This will typically reduce the Miller effect and increase the bandwidth of the amplifier.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] Alternatively, a voltage buffer may be used before the amplifier input, reducing the effective source impedance seen by the input terminals.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] This lowers the $RC$ time constant of the circuit and typically increases the bandwidth.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] The Miller capacitance can be mitigated by employing neutralisation.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] This can be achieved by feeding back an additional signal that is in phase opposition to that which is present at the stage output.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] By feeding back such a signal via a suitable capacitor, the Miller effect can, at least in theory, be eliminated entirely.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] In practice, variations in the capacitance of individual amplifying devices coupled with other stray capacitances, makes it difficult to design a circuit such that total cancellation occurs.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] Historically, it was not unknown for the neutralising capacitor to be selected on test to match the amplifying device, particularly with early transistors that had very poor bandwidths.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] The derivation of the phase inverted signal usually requires an inductive component such as a choke or an inter-stage transformer.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] In vacuum tubes, an extra grid (the screen grid) could be inserted between the control grid and the anode.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] This had the effect of screening the anode from the grid and substantially reducing the capacitance between them.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] While the technique was initially successful other factors limited the advantage of this technique as the bandwidth of tubes improved.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] Later tubes had to employ very small grids (the frame grid) to reduce the capacitance to allow the device to operate at frequencies that were impossible with the screen grid.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] Figure 2A shows an example of Figure 1 where the impedance coupling the input to the output is the coupling capacitor $C_{C}$ .
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] Thévenin voltage source $V_{A}$ drives the circuit with Thévenin resistance $R_{A}$ .
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] The output impedance of the amplifier is considered low enough that the relationship $V_{o}=-A_{v}V_{i}$ is presumed to hold.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] At the output, $Z_{L}$ serves as the load.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] (The load is irrelevant to this discussion: it just provides a path for the current to leave the circuit.) In Figure 2A, the coupling capacitor delivers a current ${\textstyle j\omega C_{C}(V_{i}-V_{o})}$ to the output node.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] Figure 2B shows a circuit electrically identical to Figure 2A using Miller's theorem.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] The coupling capacitor is replaced on the input side of the circuit by the Miller capacitance $C_{M}$ , which draws the same current from the driver as the coupling capacitor in Figure 2A.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] Therefore, the driver sees exactly the same loading in both circuits.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] In order for the Miller capacitance to draw the same current in Figure 2B as the coupling capacitor in Figure 2A, the Miller transformation is used to relate $C_{M}$ to $C_{C}$ .
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] This result is the same as $C_{M}$ of the *Derivation Section*.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] The present example with *$A_{v}$* frequency independent shows the implications of the Miller effect, and therefore of $C_{C}$ , upon the frequency response of this circuit, and is typical of the impact of the Miller effect (see, for example, common source).
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] If *$C_{C}$* is 0, the output voltage of the circuit is simply $A_{v}v_{A}$ , independent of frequency.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] However, when *$C_{C}$* is not zero, Figure 2B shows the large Miller capacitance appears at the input of the circuit.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] and rolls off with frequency once frequency is high enough that ω*CMRA* ≥ 1.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] In analog amplifiers this curtailment of frequency response is a major implication of the Miller effect.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] In this example, the frequency ω*3dB* such that ω*3dB* *CMRA* = 1 marks the end of the low-frequency response region and sets the bandwidth or cutoff frequency of the amplifier.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] The effect of *C*M upon the amplifier bandwidth is greatly reduced for low impedance drivers (*C*M *R*A is small if *R*A is small).
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] Consequently, one way to minimize the Miller effect upon bandwidth is to use a low-impedance driver, for example, by interposing a voltage follower stage between the driver and the amplifier, which reduces the apparent driver impedance seen by the amplifier.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] The output voltage of this simple circuit is always *Av vi*.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] However, real amplifiers have output resistance.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] If the amplifier output resistance is included in the analysis, the output voltage exhibits a more complex frequency response and the impact of the frequency-dependent current source on the output side must be taken into account.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] Ordinarily these effects show up only at frequencies much higher than the roll-off due to the Miller capacitance, so the analysis presented here is adequate to determine the useful frequency range of an amplifier dominated by the Miller effect.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] This example also assumes *Av* is frequency independent, but more generally there is frequency dependence of the amplifier contained implicitly in *Av*.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] Such frequency dependence of *Av* also makes the Miller capacitance frequency dependent, so interpretation of *CM* as a capacitance becomes more difficult.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] However, ordinarily any frequency dependence of *Av* arises only at frequencies much higher than the roll-off with frequency caused by the Miller effect, so for frequencies up to the Miller-effect roll-off of the gain, *Av* is accurately approximated by its low-frequency value.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] Determination of *CM* using *Av* at low frequencies is the so-called **Miller approximation**.
[src:gate-driver/miller-effect] With the Miller approximation, *CM* becomes frequency independent, and its interpretation as a capacitance at low frequencies is secure.
